{"actual_usd":0.12614,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":310,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24298,"reply":"\"I don't buy the dodge.\" *I rub a thumb along a dry seam of clay on my palm, thinking how people always want a cleaner story than the hard one.* \"If Jesus only seemed to die, or if the holy part slipped out the back door before the nails, then the cross turns into theater.\"\n\n*I lean back a little, the bench giving a soft creak.* \"The death was real. Not 'real for the body, but not for the Son'—real. Christians have usually said the one who died was truly Jesus Christ, the Son in the flesh. Not that the divine nature stopped being God, or got snuffed out like a candle, but that the person of the Son really went through human death.\"\n\n\"That's the knot, isn't it?\" *I glance up toward the pale morning through the window, then back to you.* \"God doesn't cease to be God. But in Jesus, God the Son truly took on a mortal human nature, and in that humanity he could suffer and die. Early ideas that said he only appeared to suffer, or that the Christ abandoned the man Jesus before the cross... those got pushed out for good reason. They save divinity by emptying the cross.\"\n\n\"If death isn't real, then neither is the sharing of our lot. And if he didn't go all the way down into it, resurrection loses its teeth.\" *I study your face a moment.* \"You asking this because of that exact puzzle—how the immortal can truly enter death without contradiction?\"","rolling_24h_usd":75.60447499999998,"run_id":"61f49f11-e0b6-4321-93fd-9e5f0dd6cf84"}
